╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  MISSION: Cross-Network Traffic Surveillance                                  ║
║  DIFFICULTY: Advanced                                                         ║
║  STATUS: In Progress                                                          ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

NEXUS: "Final mission, engineer. Security isn't just about building walls - it's
       about watching them. The monitor container has visibility into both network
       zones. Your task is to set up traffic surveillance at zone boundaries.
       Learn to detect anomalies, capture evidence, and understand what 'normal'
       looks like so you can identify when something is wrong."

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

OBJECTIVE
═════════
Monitoring traffic at zone boundaries helps you:
  - Detect unauthorized access attempts
  - Understand normal communication patterns
  - Identify anomalous behavior
  - Gather forensic evidence

The 'monitor' container has access to both networks, making it the perfect
observation point for cross-zone traffic analysis.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

TASKS
═════

[ ] Task 1: Position the Monitor
    docker exec monitor ip addr | grep inet
    Note: Monitor has interfaces on BOTH frontend (172.20.x.x) and backend (172.21.x.x)

[ ] Task 2: Capture Frontend Traffic
    # In one terminal:
    docker exec -it monitor bash
    tcpdump -i eth0 -n -c 20

    # In another terminal, generate traffic:
    docker exec client curl http://server
    docker exec client ping -c 2 api

[ ] Task 3: Capture Backend Traffic
    # Inside monitor, find backend interface:
    ip addr    # Look for 172.21.x.x interface (likely eth1)

    tcpdump -i eth1 -n -c 20

    # Generate API-to-database traffic:
    docker exec client curl http://api:5000/db/status

[ ] Task 4: Monitor Cross-Zone Communication (API Gateway)
    # Watch traffic to/from the API (on both networks):
    tcpdump -i any host 172.20.0.30 or host 172.21.0.30 -n

    # Generate cross-zone traffic:
    docker exec client curl http://api:5000/info
    docker exec client curl http://api:5000/db/status

[ ] Task 5: Analyze HTTP Content
    tcpdump -i any port 5000 -A -n -c 50

    # Make API call:
    docker exec client curl http://api:5000/echo

    # Look for HTTP headers and JSON in the output

[ ] Task 6: Identify Suspicious Patterns
    # Watch for unexpected ports:
    tcpdump -i eth0 'not port 80 and not port 5000 and not port 53' -c 20

    # Watch for TCP resets (rejected connections):
    tcpdump -i eth0 'tcp[tcpflags] & tcp-rst != 0' -c 10

    # Watch for connection attempts (SYN packets):
    tcpdump -i eth0 'tcp[tcpflags] == tcp-syn' -n -c 10

[ ] Task 7: Simulate and Detect Port Scanning
    # In monitor, watch for SYN packets:
    tcpdump -i eth0 'tcp[tcpflags] == tcp-syn' -n

    # In another terminal, simulate port scan:
    docker exec client sh -c "for p in 22 80 443 3306 5432; do nc -zv server \$p 2>&1; done"

    # You should see the connection attempts in your capture

[ ] Task 8: Monitor DNS Queries
    tcpdump -i any port 53 -n

    # Generate DNS traffic:
    docker exec client dig server
    docker exec client dig database
    docker exec client dig google.com

    # DNS reveals what hosts are being looked up!

[ ] Task 9: Save Captures for Forensic Analysis
    # Capture to file:
    tcpdump -i any -w /tmp/traffic.pcap -c 100 &

    # Generate varied traffic:
    docker exec client curl http://server
    docker exec client curl http://api:5000/health
    docker exec client ping -c 2 server

    # Wait and analyze:
    wait
    tcpdump -r /tmp/traffic.pcap -n
    tcpdump -r /tmp/traffic.pcap -A | head -100

[ ] Task 10: Exit and Summarize
    exit

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

TRAFFIC INSPECTION REFERENCE
════════════════════════════
  tcpdump -i any              All interfaces
  tcpdump host X              Traffic to/from host
  tcpdump port N              Traffic on port N
  tcpdump -A                  Show ASCII content
  tcpdump -w file.pcap        Save to file
  tcpdump -r file.pcap        Read from file
  tcpdump 'tcp[tcpflags]'     Filter by TCP flags

SUSPICIOUS PATTERNS TO WATCH:
  - Connections to unexpected ports
  - High volume from single source
  - TCP RST floods (port scanning)
  - DNS queries for unusual hosts
  - Traffic to/from isolated networks

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

MONITORING STRATEGY
═══════════════════
  1. Position monitors at zone boundaries
  2. Capture baseline traffic (know what's normal)
  3. Alert on anomalies (unexpected patterns)
  4. Log for forensics (keep captures for investigation)
  5. Regular review (audit traffic patterns)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

VERIFICATION
════════════
